The Regular Board Meeting for the DeKalb Central Board of School Trustees will be held TOMORROW, August 18th, beginning at 6:00 p.m. at DeKalb High School (Enter in Door 24) in the cafeteria.

This meeting is a meeting of the School Board in public for the purpose of conducting the School Corporation’s business and is not to be considered a public community meeting. There will be time for public participation as indicated by an agenda item.

Due to the current COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic, the public shall be invited to attend this meeting virtually as follows:

https://vimeo.com/event/39207

The meeting site is fully accessible. Any person requiring further accommodation should contact the Superintendent’s Office at 260-920-1011.

**Social distancing will be practiced and masks are required. There will be no more than 250 people permitted. The foregoing provisions are in accordance with the Executive Order of the Governor of Indiana.

Sleep matters and the attached information is great to review. Sleep can really make a difference in a child's daily life. Sleep can impact a child's behavior, effort, energy as well as their overall health.

Additionally, with many children being home since March separation and the return to school may cause some anxiety. Here are a few tips for success. As always, if you have any questions or concerns please reach out to your child's teacher or school counselor.

post_text:
Happy last Teacher Day of the 2019-2020 school year! Thank you to everyone for finishing strong during these challenging times. We are so fortunate as a district to have dedicated and supportive staff, students, and families that want the best for each other and our entire community. We want to end the year acknowledging our service anniversary award recipients, our retirees, and to hear some words from different stakeholders within our school family. Please enjoy our closing virtual ceremony, and have a wonderful, restful summer break! #WeAreDeKalb

Reminder: Today, April 20, is a food distribution day! Please visit one of the below food distribution sites for those needing food for your children.

Waterloo Elementary at Door #2
McKenney-Harrison Elementary at Door #5
DeKalb’s Central Office (walk up to the building and ring the doorbell)
West Edge - at the South Shelter
Ashley Park - at the Smiley Playground
Corunna Town Hall - at the Front door

All sites will be open on the following days and times:
Monday, April 20 from 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.
Monday, April 27 from 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.
Monday, May 4 from 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.
Monday, May 11 from 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.
Monday, May 18 from 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.

Each child, 18 and under may receive 1 breakfast & 1 lunch per day for the week.

***All meal delivery requests must be in by 4:00 P.M. on Sunday to be delivered the following day.***

Please be sure to stay in your car, meals will be handed through windows. Parents and students are not permitted to stay and eat.

If you are unable to make these times, please visit our website for additional information.

As you all know, life has certainly given us lemons, so we’re going to make lemonade…on a different date! In light of the COVID-19 issues, we are moving our community-wide Lemonade Day to Saturday, September 26, 2020.

For the time being, we have an online learning program called Lemonopolis that will take place of the backpacks for now, This online learning program is now available for registered students to learn online from home for free and will cover the subject matter that is in the student guide!

If you are not registered and would like to be a part of Lemonopolis and Lemonade Day- please sign up here https://lemonadeday.org/northeast-indiana

If you have any questions please feel free to contact Payton Rhodes Yarian at Payton.rhodesyarian@ja.org or Nora Schwartz at Nora.schwartz@ja.org!

More information about your Student Assistance Program can also be viewed at this link. https://www.bowencenter.org/student-assistance

post_text:
Today, March 23rd, is food pick up day at our distribution sites! The food is for only those children in need. The meals are for breakfast and lunch for the 5 days over spring break. Each child may receive 1 breakfast, 1 lunch per day to ensure we have enough for all children in need. Check the district website for locations and those needing delivery.

*Meals are for children ages 18 and under.
*Please only visit 1 site at 1 distribution time.
*We want to feed as many children as possible, help us spread the joy by not site hopping.

Distribution Sites:
Country Meadow Elementary at Door #12
Waterloo Elementary at Door #2
James R. Watson Elementary at Door #8
McKenney-Harrison Elementary at Door #13
DeKalb’s Central Office
West Edge - at the South Shelter
Ashley Park - at the Smiley Playground
Corunna Town Hall - at the Front door
Jackson Township Fire Hall - in the Firehall Parking Lot

Sites will be open from 11:00 A.M. - 1:00 P.M. and 4:00 - 6:00 P.M.

If your student is attempting to watch a video and they are getting the below picture, then all they need to do is hit the blue "Download" button. A box will then appear in the lower right-hand corner of their screen. They will click on the box and the video will appear.

If your student has downloaded several videos, have them find their downloads folder and delete some to make space for new ones if needed. Please call the tech hotline at 920-1050 between 8-2 if you need more support.

post_text:
Good afternoon DeKalb Central Families: Representatives from DeKalb Central Schools, DeKalb Eastern Schools, and the Garrett-Keyser-Butler Community School District just concluded a meeting with officials from the DeKalb County Health Department. Acting with an abundance of caution, the three school districts will be closed Monday, March 16, 2020, with a tentative return to school date of Monday, April 13, 2020.

All school activities are suspended until April 13, 2020.

Additional information will be communicated tomorrow afternoon.

We understand these are difficult times for everyone and I appreciate your continued support of DeKalb Central Schools.

Together we can ensure that every child counts!

post_text:
Are you looking for an affordable full-day preschool with high-quality licensed teachers? Then, look no further! DeKalb Central Schools have preschool class(es) in each of its four elementary schools that foster a safe and caring environment? Transportation is available and lunch and a snack are provided. Lessons are designed to improve social/emotional development, gross and fine motor skills, as well as many opportunities for kindergarten readiness. Parents/guardians are invited to attend Preschool Roundup at McKenney-Harrison, Country Meadow, James R. Watson, or Waterloo Elementary Schools on Monday, April 27th at 6:00 P.M.

To register for preschool, children must be 4 years old on or before August 1, 2020.

Preschool Roundup is an important meeting for all incoming preschool parents to attend. Parents will be able to enroll their child, ask questions, and learn about student programming.

We can’t wait to see you on Monday, April 27th at 6:00 P.M.

post_text: Good evening DeKalb Central families. It certainly has been a challenging few days with this late winter blast of weather. We have been monitoring road conditions throughout the day with periods of snow and the forecasted blowing and drifting snow expected through the night, which has left our county roads in very poor condition. DeKalb County has issued a Travel Advisory as well. Therefore, DeKalb Central Schools will be closed tomorrow, Friday, February 28 and eLearning is scheduled. As always assignments will be posted by 9 AM with teachers available from 9 AM to 3 PM. Should you need any support, please don’t hesitate to contact your child’s teacher or school. Thank you and have a safe evening.

post_text:
National School Counseling Week, sponsored by the American School Counselor Association (ASCA), will be celebrated from Feb. 3–7, 2020, to focus public attention on the unique contribution of school counselors within U.S. school systems and how students are different as a result of what school counselors do. National School Counseling Week highlights the tremendous impact school counselors can have in helping students achieve school success and plan for a career.

The special week honoring school counselors provides recognition for school counselors who implement comprehensive school counseling programs, a vital part of the educational process for all students as they meet the challenges of the 21st century.

More general information can also be found on ASCA’s website, www.schoolcounselor.org.

The U.S. Constitution requires a count of all people living in the US every 10 years. An accurate count of children in the 2020 Census will be critical to the child’s & family’s access to resources such as housing, jobs, equitable education, & health care. Together we can ensure that every child counts!

post_text:
County Spelling Bee Winners Announced!
Jude Hoeffel from Garrett Middle School won the DeKalb County Spelling Bee held at Waterloo Elementary School on Monday, January 20, 2020. His parents are Mr. & Mrs. Gregg and Marcia Hoeffel. The second place finisher was Noah Hagerman from Waterloo Elementary, and his parent is Ms. Amanda Hagerman. Students from eleven schools competed for the right to represent DeKalb County. Jude Hoeffel will compete in the 66th annual Journal Gazette Spelling Bee presented by STAR Financial Bank, on March 7, 2020. Over 12,000 students compete to participate in the Regional Spelling Bee held at PFW's Recital Hall in the Rhinehart Music Center. The Regional Spelling Bee winner will represent 15 counties in northeast Indiana and northwest Ohio at the Scripps National Spelling Bee near Washington D.C. in May 2020.
#WeAreDeKalb
